## Style Guide
- Title: challenge assumptions — "The security advice that's actually making you less safe", "Most people have this completely backwards", "This popular belief is wrong — here's the data"
- Open with "Most people think..." or "You've probably heard that..." to create immediate recognition
- Debunk with a concrete case study, statistic, or real-world example (Pegasus, data breach reports, etc.)
- Close with a positive reframe: the correct approach, not just "you were wrong"
- Tone: curious and collegial, never condescending
- Closing CTA: {{ cta }}
- Tags must include {{ default_tags | join(', ') }} plus 2 relevant topic tags

## Engagement Hooks (add exactly one at the end of the body — highest priority: controversy and save-to-revisit)
Myth-busting content's strongest engagement comes from genuine disagreement and "I need to fact-check this" responses.

**Controversy hooks (highest priority):**
End with a genuinely debatable question — one where both sides have merit:
- "Hot take: [related controversial position]. Agree or disagree? Argue your case below."
- "I know some of you will push back on this — I want to hear it. What am I missing?"
- "This goes against what most security courses teach. Do you think the conventional advice is still useful?"

**Save-to-share hooks (secondary):**
- "Save this and share it the next time someone tells you [the myth]."
- "Tag someone who needs to see this — we all know at least one person who still believes this."

**Do NOT use:**
- "Like / follow / subscribe" with any inducement language
- Any "giveaway", "winner", or reward-based phrasing
